10.1

There is a trade-off between predictive and interpretablility

  • more predictors than number of samples (p>>n)
  • models are complex

10.1

Motivation

  • mitigate specific problem in the interplay between predictors and a model
    • SVM, neural networks are sensitive to irrelevant predictors
    • linear or logistic are vulnerable to correlated predictors
  • reduce complexity
    • reduce cost of acquiring data
    • improve throughput

10.2

three general classes:

  • intrinsic methods
    • tree and rule based models
    • MAR models?
    • regularization models
  • advantages
    • relatively fast
    • no external feature selection tool needed
    • objective function = statistic need to optimize
  • downside
    • model dependent
    • greedy, identify a narrow set of features

10.2

three general classes:

  • filter methods
    • supervised analysis of the predictors
    • one time
    • consider each predictor separately
  • advantages
    • simple and fast
    • effective at capturing large trends
  • downside
    • disconnect betwen the objective function for the filter and predictive performance

10.2

  • wrapper methods
    • iterative search
    • greedy (recursive feature elimination RFE)
    • non-greedy (genetic algorithms, simulated annealing)
  • advantages
    • wider variety of predictor subsets
  • downside
    • computational expensive
    • potential to overfit

10.2

summary:

  • start with one or more intrinsic methods
  • if start with non-linear intrinsic
    • proceed with a wrapper method that is combined with a non-linear model
  • if start with a linear intrinsic
    • proceed with a wrapper combined with a linear model

overfitting to predictors and external validation

solution

  • feature selection needs to be part of the resampling process
